<emphasis bold="true" box="[444,675,1016,1040]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="3245">Saccostrea cucullata</emphasis>
(Born, 1778)
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[159,1116,1079,1337]" box="[199,1027,1079,1104]" pageId="17" pageNumber="3245">
<emphasis box="[199,294,1080,1104]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="3245">Habitat.</emphasis>
Attached to rocks and forming layered beds in the intertidal.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="3245" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="17.[159,1116,1079,1337]" pageId="17" pageNumber="3245">
<emphasis box="[199,338,1114,1138]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="3245">Distribution.</emphasis>
Although reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="FAURE, G." box="[611,758,1113,1137]" pageId="17" pageNumber="3245" pagination="437 - 448" refId="ref13563" refString="FAURE, G., 1973, Contribution a l'etude de la zonation littorale sur substrats durs de l'Ile Rodrigues (Archipel des Mascareignes, Ocean Indien), Tethys, 5 (2 / 3), 437 - 448." type="journal article" year="1973">Fauré (1973)</bibRefCitation>
we could find no living examples. In Baie du Nord and Baie Topaze long-dead layered beds can be found.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[159,1116,1079,1337]" pageId="17" pageNumber="3245">
<emphasis box="[199,305,1179,1203]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="3245">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="LEGUAT, F." box="[317,476,1179,1203]" pageId="17" pageNumber="3245" refId="ref13890" refString="LEGUAT, F., 1708, The Voyage of Francois Leguat of Bresse to Rodriguez, Mauritius, Java, and the Cape of Good Hope, edited and annotated by Captain Samuel Pasfield Oliver," type="book" year="1708">Léguat (1708)</bibRefCitation>
reported eating abundant oysters from a bay adjacent to Port Mathurin, presumably Baie au Huîtres. Today living oysters are absent from all of the sheltered bays along the north coast and Baie Topaze in the west. Enquiries suggest that there is no local memory of living oyster beds and therefore that they have been dead for some 70–90 years. The cause of this
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[159,1116,1348,1474]" pageId="17" pageNumber="3245">decline could be over consumption or the siltation of these bays by terrestrial erosion.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[159,1116,1348,1474]" box="[199,537,1416,1440]" pageId="17" pageNumber="3245">
<emphasis box="[199,278,1416,1440]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="3245">Range.</emphasis>
Indo-Pacific [R/M/S].
</paragraph>
